body:
@westontrillium Thank you for the context and the clear explanations. We will make sure to echo some of what you mentioned in the presentation. We are working on a time and date (+/- in 2 weeks). 

@ckraatz 

> I'm a proponent of iteration, so I'm open to exploring ways to phase some of this in.

This proposal is meant to lay the foundations for iterations actually. We want to improve it over time and to include many of the things you and the community brought up during this process. i.e.: Merging both Static and RT governances, expanding testing and voting requirements if needed, updating the guiding principles, ... There is so much more we can do to make this process clearer and something that the community wants to use. We think this lays that groundwork and we are glad to have you here to talk about the possibilities moving forward.

As @skinkie mentioned, 20 producers requirement is very high for both voting and testing. We would have to assess wether participation increases in spec development over the next months to understand what number could best fit this idea.

@eliasmbd that’s great, I’m glad they were all involved.

@bdferris-v2 what are your thoughts about the number of Consumers and Producers the process should require to begin Testing, during Testing? Would Google accept a higher bar to Vote to Adopt that would require support from more Consumers (perhaps including Google)? 

What about the current and proposed process works or doesn’t work for Google? What hindrances does Google face in terms of testing and adopting changes, for example any currently Adopted changes that Google hasn’t implemented?

@abyrd has anyone been challenging MobilityData's role in the governance process? 

If so, I would strongly advocate for codifying and formalizing that role. A data standard needs institutional leadership behind it, and MobilityData is clearly purpose-built and qualified for that role. I would, however, suggest a role that's a bit broader and more ambitious than "Maintainer." I think "Facilitator" would be better.

@eliasmbd Did MobilityData recently change its Mission Statement? I remember looking it up and referencing it during the April 11 Industry Advisory Council meeting, and now [what I see on the website looks different](https://mobilitydata.org/what-we-do/). The "for all" language has been removed, for example, and I thought that was a powerful and admirable North Star.
